sions lie in the secular struggle of army against workers that he describes. In the introduction, Richard Graham takes issue with both authors on certain basic premises and points out implications of their essays for the understanding of North American as well as Latin American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCulture conflictzLatin America. 0aElite (Social sciences)zLatin America. 0aIndustrial relationszLatin America. 0aLatin America--Social conditions. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aBernhard, Virginia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurns, E. Bradford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard.1 aSkidmore, Thomas E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSkidmore, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTiller, Ann Q., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76457640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477305683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477305683/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK